Harvard students take a course on how to get enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has pushed all its students to sleep more in an attempt to counter the growing virile culture of studying for entire nights fueled by caffeine.
One university scholar found that university students number one in the world often have no idea of the basic concepts of taking care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, developed the course, which he considers to be the first of this type in the USA.
He had the idea of starting the course after a conference that had given the impact of sleeplessness on learning.
"At last a girl came to me and said to me, 'Why is this only now, when I'm in the last year?'
He said that no one had ever told him anything about the importance of sleep, which surprised me very much," he told The Telegraph.
The course, delivered for the first time this year, explains to students the essential concepts of how good sleep-related habits can help academic and athletic performance as well as improve general well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and Director General of Health Services at the University, said that the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students suffered from a severe sleeplessness during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive activities.
In a section there is the image of a dormitory room, where students can select cups of coffee, tents, gymnastics shoes and books to be able to know the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is influenced by sleeplessness, and the importance of a night routine.
In another section, participants are explained how the lack of long-term sleep can increase the risks of heart attacks, strokes, depression and cancer.
A map of the campus, with interactive icons, therefore encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know that it will not change the behavior of students immediately.
But we believe that they have the right to know, just as you have the right to know the health effects of choosing to smoke cigarettes," added Prof. Czeisler.
The culture of pride linked to the "white night to study", still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students lead to the lack of sleep being a constantly growing problem.
Sleeping enough and with a good quality sleep should be the "secret weapon" of the students to fight stress, fatigue, anxiety, explained and should even serve to avoid fattening because the lack of sleep brings the brain in an unprecedented way, making people constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student enrolled in the faculty of chemistry and physics, helped Professor Czeisler develop the course, after having attended one of his lessons last year in Harvard.
He explained that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to promote a course aimed at the entire campus.
The next step, he hopes, will be to ask all graduates to follow a similar study programme before enrolling in this competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler advised students to set up a wake for when they need to go to bed, as well as for when they need to wake up, and to be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can send the circadian rhythm into tilt, leading to sleeping problems.
