Red tide update: concentration decreases in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission's latest report shows a general decrease in red tide concentration in parts of Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, conditions of flowering to chutes, which suggest a decrease in concentration, are evident in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties.
The red tide bloom extends for about 130 miles of coast from the north of Pinellas County to the south of Lee County.
The cottages are located about 10 miles away from Hillsborough County but in less areas than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Easter County.
Last week an average concentration was reported in Pinellas County or off its coasts, a low to high concentration off Hillsborough County, from a bottom concentration to a high concentration in Manatee County, from a bottom concentration to a high concentration in Sarasota County or off its coasts, from a bottom concentration to an average concentration in Charlotte County, from a bottom concentration to a high concentration in Lee County or off its coasts and a low concentration in Collier County.
Cases of respiratory irritation continue to be reported in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
While last week no cases were reported in northwest Florida.
